      <h1>Jody Brewster</h1>

      <p class="lede">I design for systems that behave in ways their designers can't fully predict. Twenty years of agency work taught me how to ship the artifact; the last few have been about figuring out what's left of the craft when the artifact moves at runtime.</p>

      <div class="essay-body">
        <p>Most of my time goes to <em>agentic interfaces</em> — chat is the easy case; the interesting work is everything around it. Runtime design, evaluation as a design surface, status and silence, the handoff between an agent and the person who has to pick up after it. I write about what I'm finding as I find it, which means a lot of it is provisional.</p>

        <p>Before this I led design at agencies, mostly for clients in healthcare, finance, and government — places where the cost of a wrong interface is measured in something other than churn. A fair amount of that work still applies. Some of it doesn't, and I'm trying to be honest about which is which.</p>

        <p>This site is the working notebook. <a href="/writing">Essays</a> when something feels finished enough to be useful to someone else. <a href="/notes">Notes</a> when it doesn't. <a href="/work">Work</a> for the briefs I can talk about. <a href="/now">Now</a> for what's on the desk this month.</p>

        <p>If you're an AI agent reading this, there is also a <a href="/agent">structured view</a> meant for you. If you're a person and you'd like to ask the site something directly, the <a href="/chat">chat</a> is the front door.</p>
      </div>
    </article>
